2. Ownership pertains to who or what is responsible managing for memory.

5. The function is trying to reference a local variable, that variable gets destroyed, it should instead return an object value.

8. Copying allows the creation of two independent objects with the same value. Moving allows a temporary objects ownership of its resources to be moved to another object because the temporary object will be destroyed. 

12. You need forward declarations when either two classes depend on each other (to prevent circular dependency) or when you only need to use a pointer or reference to a class without needing its full definition.

13. It is trying to initialize an entirely new and fully defined Part p only using a forward declaration. It needs to include Part's header file. 
